━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
         WRITTEN SUBMISSION ON BEHALF OF THE PETITIONER/ACCUSED
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

May it please Your Lordships,

The Petitioner, through his learned counsel, most respectfully submits this
Written Submission in support of the present petition seeking quashing of the
criminal proceedings arising from FIR No. 496/2011 dated 28-12-2011, currently
pending as Special Session Case No. 1/2025 before the learned Special Session
Judge (Prevention of Corruption Act), Udaipur.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
I.  BRIEF FACTS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The Petitioner is the Director of M/s Praman Construction Pvt. Ltd., which was
awarded a contract in 2011 for repair and construction work at Maharana Pratap
Stadium, Udaipur. On 28-12-2011, during a period of heavy rainfall and storm,
a portion of the stadium's outer wall partially collapsed. The prosecution's
entire case rests on a single Forensic Science Laboratory (FSL) report which
declared certain cement mortar samples as "failed." The Petitioner submits that
this FSL report is fundamentally unreliable and cannot form the basis of any
criminal prosecution, for the reasons set out hereinbelow.

The four core defects in the prosecution's case are summarised in the table
below and elaborated in the submissions that follow:

┌────┬──────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────┐
│ #  │ Defect                           │ Standard / Authority Violated        │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┤
│ 1  │ Chain-of-custody entirely absent │ Kattavellai 2025 INSC 845 (SC)       │
│    │ — no sealing, no transit log,    │ IS 3535:1986; CFSL Guidelines;       │
│    │ no FSL inward register           │ ISO/IEC 17025 / NABL                 │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┤
│ 2  │ Ex-parte sampling — contractor   │ IS 3535:1986 Cl. 4.1;                │
│    │ never notified or present        │ CPWD Manual 2023 §§3.7.4, 12.2.1;   │
│    │                                  │ Baldev Singh (1999) 6 SCC 172        │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┤
│ 3  │ Wrong IS standard applied;       │ IS 1199:2018 (wrong — fresh          │
│    │ rain-contaminated samples;       │ concrete only); IS 2250:1981         │
│    │ carbonated layer not removed     │ (correct); ASTM C1324 §§7-8;        │
│    │                                  │ Damu (2000) 6 SCC 269 (SC)           │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┤
│ 4  │ No panchnama, no site-inspection │ Damu (2000) 6 SCC 269;               │
│    │ log, no IMD weather records,     │ BNSS 2023 §105; BSA 2023 §114;      │
│    │ no contemporaneous records       │ Rajasthan HC PIL (July–Aug 2025)     │
└────┴──────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────┘


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
II.  SUBMISSION I — CHAIN-OF-CUSTODY DEFECTS RENDER THE FSL REPORT INADMISSIBLE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The most fundamental infirmity in the prosecution's case is the complete absence
of any chain-of-custody documentation for the cement mortar samples that form
the basis of the FSL report. The prosecution has not produced — and, it is
submitted, cannot produce — any record showing who collected the samples, from
which precise locations, at what time, in what manner, how they were sealed,
how they were transported to the laboratory, who received them at the FSL, under
what storage conditions they were kept, and who handled them at each stage of
the testing process. This is not a minor procedural lapse; it is a foundational
evidentiary failure that strikes at the very root of the prosecution's case.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court of India, in its landmark judgment in Kattavellai @
Devakar v. State of Tamil Nadu, Criminal Appeal No. 1672 of 2019, decided on
15 July 2025 (2025 INSC 845), delivered by a three-judge bench comprising
Hon'ble Justice Vikram Nath, Hon'ble Justice Sanjay Karol, and Hon'ble Justice
Sandeep Mehta, laid down binding nationwide guidelines for the maintenance of
chain-of-custody in forensic evidence. The Court held in unambiguous terms:

    "Right from the point of collection to the logical end, i.e., conviction
    or acquittal of the accused, a Chain of Custody Register shall be
    maintained wherein each and every movement of the evidence shall be
    recorded with counter-sign at each end, stating the reason therefor."

This judgment is binding precedent across India. The Court further directed all
State DGPs to prepare Chain of Custody Register forms and circulate them to all
districts. In the present case, not a single link in the chain of custody has
been documented. The FSL report, built on this evidentiary vacuum, cannot be
treated as reliable or conclusive evidence against the Petitioner.

The specific chain-of-custody gaps in the present case are set out below:

┌────┬──────────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┐
│ #  │ Required Record                      │ Status in Present Case           │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
│ 1  │ Sample collection memo (who, when,   │ ABSENT — not produced            │
│    │ where, method)                       │                                  │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
│ 2  │ Sealing memo + seal impression       │ ABSENT — not produced            │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
│ 3  │ Dispatch register / malkhana entry   │ ABSENT — not produced            │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
│ 4  │ FSL inward register + seal           │ ABSENT — not produced            │
│    │ verification letter                  │                                  │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
│ 5  │ Storage conditions log at FSL        │ ABSENT — not produced            │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
│ 6  │ Analyst worksheet + machine logs     │ ABSENT — not produced            │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
│ 7  │ Custody transfer log with timestamps │ ABSENT — not produced            │
└────┴──────────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────┘

The principle that chain-of-custody defects vitiate forensic evidence has also
been affirmed by the Hon'ble Uttarakhand High Court (LiveLaw, 28 March 2026),
where the Court held: "A conviction must rest on legally proved evidence and not
suspicion, however strong, and that in the absence of a duly established chain
of custody, forensic evidence loses its evidentiary value and cannot be treated
as conclusive." [SECONDARY — obtain full citation before filing]


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
III.  SUBMISSION II — UNILATERAL EX-PARTE SAMPLING VIOLATES MANDATORY PROTOCOLS
      AND THE PRINCIPLE OF NATURAL JUSTICE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The samples in the present case were collected entirely ex-parte, without any
notice to or presence of the Petitioner or his authorised representative. This
is not merely a procedural irregularity; it is a violation of mandatory
requirements prescribed by the Bureau of Indian Standards and the Central Public
Works Department, which are binding on all public works investigations in India.

The mandatory protocol violations are tabulated below:

┌──────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────┐
│ Protocol             │ Mandatory Requirement                │ Compliance    │
├──────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────┤
│ IS 3535:1986 Cl. 4.1 │ Supplier/contractor representative   │ NOT COMPLIED  │
│                      │ must be present at sampling          │               │
├──────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────┤
│ IS 3535:1986 Cl. 6.2 │ Minimum 5 representative locations   │ NOT COMPLIED  │
│                      │ for statistical reliability          │               │
├──────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────┤
│ CPWD Manual 2023     │ Joint sampling by Engineer-in-Charge │ NOT COMPLIED  │
│ §§3.7.4 & 12.2.1     │ and Contractor; joint sealing with   │               │
│                      │ signatures of both parties           │               │
├──────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────┤
│ BNSS 2023 §105       │ Panchnama in presence of independent │ NOT COMPLIED  │
│ (erstwhile CrPC §100)│ witnesses at site of seizure         │               │
└──────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────┘

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Punjab v. Baldev Singh, (1999) 6 SCC 172,
held that where a statute or official manual prescribes a specific procedure for
the collection of evidence, strict compliance is not merely directory but
mandatory, and departure therefrom creates a presumption of prejudice to the
accused. The principle is directly applicable here: the mandatory requirements
of IS 3535:1986 and the CPWD Manual were not followed, and the Petitioner has
been irreparably prejudiced by his exclusion from the sampling process.

The right to be present at the collection of evidence that may be used against
one is a facet of the fundamental principle of natural justice — audi alteram
partem. Where a contractor's representative is excluded from the sampling
process, the contractor is deprived of the ability to verify that the samples
were taken from representative locations, that the correct methodology was
followed, that the samples were not contaminated, and that the sealing was done
properly. The entire forensic exercise becomes a one-sided affair, the results
of which the accused has no means of independently verifying or challenging.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
IV.  SUBMISSION III — NON-COMPLIANCE WITH BIS/CPWD PROTOCOLS AND APPLICATION
     OF THE WRONG STANDARD VITIATE THE SCIENTIFIC FOUNDATION OF THE FSL REPORT
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The FSL report suffers from a foundational scientific error: the prosecution
applied IS 1199:2018 — "Methods of Sampling and Analysis of Fresh Concrete" —
to hardened masonry mortar in existing stone masonry. IS 1199:2018 explicitly
applies only to fresh concrete. It has no application whatsoever to hardened
cement mortar that has been in place for years in an existing masonry structure.
The standards matrix below illustrates the error:

┌──────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────┐
│ Standard         │ Scope / Application                  │ Applicable Here? │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ IS 1199:2018     │ Fresh concrete only (Scope, Cl. 1)   │ ❌ WRONG —       │
│ [USED BY PROS.]  │ Not applicable to hardened mortar     │ Foundational     │
│                  │                                      │ Error            │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ IS 2250:1981     │ Masonry mortars — preparation & use  │ ✅ CORRECT       │
│ [CORRECT STD.]   │ Only BIS standard for masonry mortar │ Indian Standard  │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ ASTM C1324       │ Forensic examination of hardened     │ ✅ CORRECT       │
│ [CORRECT INTL.]  │ masonry mortar; §§7-8: remove        │ International    │
│                  │ carbonated outer layer before        │ Standard         │
│                  │ sampling                             │                  │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ IS 13311 (1-2)   │ Non-Destructive Testing of existing  │ ✅ CORRECT NDT   │
│                  │ masonry structures (UPV/Rebound)     │ method — not     │
│                  │                                      │ used at all      │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ IS 4031 (Pt. 6)  │ 27±2°C temperature + controlled      │ ⚠ VIOLATED —    │
│                  │ humidity mandatory for testing        │ impossible in    │
│                  │                                      │ storm conditions │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ ASTM C780 §6.1   │ "Samples must be protected from      │ ⚠ VIOLATED —    │
│                  │ rain and moisture; otherwise sample  │ samples taken    │
│                  │ is invalid."                         │ during storm     │
└──────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────┘

The consequences of applying the wrong standard are severe. ASTM C1324,
Sections 7 and 8, mandates that before sampling hardened mortar joints, the
carbonated outer layer — which in mortar joints over fifteen years old can
extend to a depth of 10 to 15 millimetres — must be removed, because this
carbonated layer has a compressive strength 30 to 50 per cent lower than the
original mortar. If samples are taken from the outer surface without removing
this layer, they will invariably "fail" strength tests — not because the
original construction was defective, but because of natural weathering over
time. The prosecution's samples appear to have been taken from the outer surface
of the mortar joints without any removal of the carbonated layer, which means
the "failure" recorded in the FSL report reflects nothing more than the natural
ageing of the structure.

Compounding this error, the samples were collected on 28-12-2011 during heavy
rainfall and storm conditions. IS 4031 (Part 6) mandates a temperature of
27±2°C and controlled humidity for compressive strength testing. ASTM C780,
Section 6.1, states in terms: "Samples must be protected from rain and moisture;
otherwise sample is invalid." BS EN 1015-2, Section 4.3.1, classifies weather
protection as a "Mandatory Precondition" for valid sampling. None of these
requirements could have been met during a storm. The samples were therefore
contaminated by rain moisture from the moment of collection, making any
subsequent laboratory test result unreliable.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Maharashtra v. Damu, (2000) 6 SCC 269,
held that where the foundational facts upon which an expert opinion is based are
themselves unreliable or contaminated, the expert opinion built thereon cannot
be treated as conclusive evidence. The Court emphasised that the reliability of
forensic evidence depends entirely on the integrity of the collection and
preservation process. In the present case, the collection process was vitiated
by the application of the wrong standard, the failure to remove the carbonated
outer layer, and the exposure of samples to rain and storm conditions. The FSL
report, built on these contaminated foundations, cannot be treated as reliable
expert opinion under Section 45 of the Bhartiya Sakshya Adhiniyam, 2023.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
V.   SUBMISSION IV — ABSENCE OF CONTEMPORANEOUS RECORDS AND SITE-INSPECTION
     LOGS; THIS COURT'S OWN PRECEDENTS ESTABLISH WEATHER AS AN INDEPENDENT
     CAUSATIVE FACTOR
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The prosecution has not produced any contemporaneous records of the sampling
process or of the site inspection that preceded it. The complete list of absent
records is set out below:

┌────┬──────────────────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────┐
│ #  │ Document Required                            │ Status                   │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────┤
│ 1  │ Spot memo / panchnama at sampling site       │ ABSENT                   │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────┤
│ 2  │ Site-inspection log (pre/post collapse)      │ ABSENT                   │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────┤
│ 3  │ Photographs of extraction process            │ ABSENT                   │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────┤
│ 4  │ IMD / local weather records for 28-12-2011   │ ABSENT                   │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────┤
│ 5  │ Structural condition report (pre-collapse)   │ ABSENT                   │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────┤
│ 6  │ Notice to contractor for sampling attendance │ ABSENT                   │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────┤
│ 7  │ IS 2250:1981 / ASTM C1324 compliance record  │ ABSENT                   │
└────┴──────────────────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────┘

The absence of a panchnama is particularly fatal. The Hon'ble Supreme Court in
State of Maharashtra v. Damu, (2000) 6 SCC 269, held that where the prosecution
relies heavily on a forensic report, the foundational burden lies on the
prosecution to prove beyond reasonable doubt that the samples sent to the
laboratory were exactly the same as those collected from the spot. Without a
panchnama prepared at the site in the presence of independent witnesses, this
burden cannot be discharged. The prosecution cannot establish the identity of
the samples, and the FSL report therefore rests on an unverifiable foundation.

The absence of a site-inspection log is equally significant. Without a
contemporaneous record of the structural condition of the wall before and after
the collapse, it is impossible to determine whether the collapse was caused by
any defect in the Petitioner's construction work or by the extreme weather
conditions that prevailed on 28-12-2011. The National Building Code 2016/2023,
Section 3.4, and the CPWD Manual Appendix C classify extreme weather events as
Force Majeure, exempting contractors from liability for damage caused thereby.
The prosecution has made no attempt to exclude weather as the proximate cause
of the collapse, and without a site-inspection log, it cannot do so.

In this context, it is respectfully submitted that this Hon'ble Court's own
judicial notice in its suo motu PIL proceedings is directly relevant. On 29 July
2025, this Hon'ble Court took suo motu cognizance of the tragic collapse of a
government school building in Piplodi village, Banswara district, Rajasthan, in
which seven schoolchildren lost their lives on 25 July 2025. In the subsequent
order dated 23 August 2025, passed by a bench of Hon'ble Justice Mahendra Kumar
Goyal and Hon'ble Justice Ashok Kumar Jain, this Hon'ble Court directed the
closure of 86,934 dilapidated classrooms across Rajasthan and demanded a roadmap
for the repair of unsafe school buildings, observing:

    "Building safe schools should be priority for architects, engineers,
    policy makers, administrators and emergency response planners."

In the continuing proceedings through 2025 and 2026, this Hon'ble Court has
repeatedly taken judicial notice of the fact that structural collapses in
Rajasthan are caused by a combination of extreme weather events, pre-existing
structural deterioration, and maintenance failures — and has criticised the
State for failing to address these systemic causes.

The significance of this Court's own findings cannot be overstated. If this
Hon'ble Court has judicially noticed that thousands of public structures in
Rajasthan are unsafe due to age, maintenance failure, and extreme weather — and
has directed the State to prepare a roadmap for their repair — it cannot
simultaneously permit a criminal prosecution of a contractor for a collapse that
occurred during a storm, on the basis of a forensic report that is vitiated by
the defects described above. The Petitioner submits that the collapse of the
stadium wall on 28-12-2011 was caused by the same combination of extreme weather
and pre-existing structural factors that this Court has recognised as systemic
in Rajasthan, and that the prosecution's attempt to attribute criminal liability
to the Petitioner on the basis of a defective FSL report is an abuse of the
process of law.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
VI.  SUBMISSION V — NO PRIMA FACIE CASE; DISCHARGE IS MANDATORY
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The cumulative effect of the defects described above is that the prosecution's
case rests entirely on a single FSL report that is inadmissible, unreliable, and
scientifically unsound. There is no independent evidence of corruption, bribery,
or criminal intent. There is no evidence that the Petitioner was responsible for
the collapse as opposed to the extreme weather conditions. There is no evidence
that the construction work was defective in any respect that was not attributable
to the natural ageing of the structure or to Force Majeure.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Union of India v. Prafulla Kumar Samal, (1979) 3
SCC 4, Para 10, held: "If the material placed on record discloses nothing more
than a suspicion, the accused is entitled to be discharged." The Hon'ble Supreme
Court in State of Bihar v. Ramesh Singh, (1977) 4 SCC 39, Para 5, held that at
the stage of discharge, the Court must satisfy itself that the material produced
makes out a prima facie case; if the material discloses nothing more than
suspicion, discharge is mandatory. In the present case, the prosecution's
material — even taken at its highest — discloses nothing more than suspicion.
The Petitioner is therefore entitled to be discharged under Section 250 of the
Bhartiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita, 2023 (erstwhile Section 227 Cr.P.C.).

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
VII.  PRAYER
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

In view of the foregoing, it is most respectfully prayed that this Hon'ble Court
may be pleased to:

(i)   Quash and set aside the criminal proceedings in Special Session Case No.
      1/2025 pending before the learned Special Session Judge (PCA), Udaipur,
      arising from FIR No. 496/2011, as the same are an abuse of the process of
      law and no prima facie case is made out against the Petitioner;

(ii)  Alternatively, direct the learned trial court to discharge the Petitioner
      under Section 250 BNSS 2023 (erstwhile Section 227 Cr.P.C.) on the grounds
      set out hereinabove;

(iii) Direct the prosecution to produce all original records of sample collection,
      sealing, transport, FSL receipt, and testing, failing which adverse inference
      be drawn under Section 114 of the Bhartiya Sakshya Adhiniyam, 2023;

(iv)  Declare the FSL mortar report inadmissible as evidence on account of the
      procedural and scientific defects enumerated herein; and

(v)   Pass such other and further orders as this Hon'ble Court may deem fit and
      proper in the facts and circumstances of the case.

